{
  "card_id": "inversion_fair_value_gap",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Inversion Fair Value Gap",
  "aliases": [
    "Fair Value Gap Inversion",
    "IFVG",
    "ifvg",
    "inversion",
    "inversion fvg",
    "Inversion FVG"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A Fair Value Gap (FVG) formed by three candles that is subsequently closed through by a full-body candle close beyond its entire range, causing a polarity flip: a bullish FVG becomes resistance, a bearish FVG becomes support. The inverted zone acts as a key reversal area on retests.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a standard Fair Value Gap (three-candle pattern with non-overlapping wicks).",
    "Wait for a subsequent candle to close completely beyond the FVG range: for a bullish FVG (BISI), a close below the entire gap; for a bearish FVG (SIBI), a close above the entire gap. A close beyond the consequent encroachment (50% of the gap) alone is insufficient.",
    "Once confirmed, the FVG becomes an inversion FVG: original support flips to resistance (bullish FVG) or resistance flips to support (bearish FVG).",
    "The inverted gap is valid only after a full-body candle close outside its extreme boundary.",
    "If price closes through the IFVG again (second inversion), the IFVG is invalidated.",
    "In a reversal sequence (TTRS), the IFVG must occur after a Turtle Soup (liquidity sweep) for confirmation.",
    "In the AMD framework, wait for the manipulation phase to complete (price sweeps liquidity and aggressively returns to range) before trading the IFVG retest.",
    "When other PD Arrays (e.g., Order Block Mean Threshold) align with the IFVG zone, it provides additional confirmation."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "After confirmation, traders may enter on a retest of the IFVG zone, with stop loss beyond the opposite swing high/low and target toward opposite liquidity (buy-side or sell-side). Entry can be optimized at the consequent encroachment (50% level) for better risk-reward. The IFVG can be combined with liquidity sweeps, AMD framework, or other PD Arrays. It is fractal and applicable across timeframes.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering prematurely when price only closes beyond the consequent encroachment but not the full FVG.",
    "Mistaking a simple retest of a FVG for an inversion when price has not closed through it.",
    "Assuming the inversion must occur immediately after the close-through; it can happen after a consolidation period.",
    "Continuing to use the FVG as support/resistance in its original direction after inversion.",
    "Ignoring risk-reward: if stop-to-target is only 1R, adjust entry to consequent encroachment.",
    "In AMD, looking for IFVG entry before manipulation phase is complete.",
    "Confusing IFVG entry with a break of structure (BOS); IFVG does not require BOS.",
    "Trying to master all reversal sequence concepts simultaneously; focus on one."
  ],
